  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>Best USB-C Hub for MacBook in 2026</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · Evaluated 7+ models</div>

      <p>Modern MacBooks and ultrabooks have traded ports for thinness, leaving you with two USB-C ports and no way to plug in a monitor, a USB drive, or an SD card at the same time. A USB-C hub restores every port you lost in a single accessory the size of a candy bar — if you pick the right one.</p>

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ranking-methodology">Ranking Methodology</a></li>
          <li><a href="#quick-comparison">Quick Comparison</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-overall">Best Overall</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-budget">Best Budget</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-guide">Buying Guide</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <h2 id="how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</h2>
      <p>We evaluated 7 USB-C hubs based on product documentation, specifications, feature analysis, and pricing comparison. Our evaluation methodology follows the <a href="/how-we-test/">ToolStep review protocol</a>, analyzing product documentation, specifications, features, and pricing. Each product was assessed across identical criteria to ensure fair comparison.</p>
      <p>We evaluated each product on four criteria: Performance (30%), Build Quality (25%), Value (20%), and Ease of Use (25%). Scores were compiled from specification analysis and feature evaluation, not marketing claims. For data transfer performance we assessed USB-A and USB-C port specifications and supported data rates. For HDMI output we evaluated resolution and refresh rate specifications. For power delivery we assessed published PD ratings and charging specifications.</p>

      <h2 id="ranking-methodology">Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>Our rankings are based on weighted scoring across four dimensions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Performance (30%)</strong> — Transfer speeds, HDMI stability, and power delivery reliability under load</li>
        <li><strong>Build Quality (25%)</strong> — Casing material, cable strain relief, and connector durability</li>
        <li><strong>Value (20%)</strong> — Price-to-port-count ratio against alternatives</li>
        <li><strong>Ease of Use (25%)</strong> — Plug-and-play setup, heat management, and port layout</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="quick-comparison">Quick Comparison</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Product</th>
            <th>Best For</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Rating</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>7-in-1 USB-C Hub (Aluminum)</strong></td>
            <td>Best Overall</td>
            <td>$35</td>
            <td>4.6/5</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Anker 555 USB-C Hub</td>
            <td>Best Budget</td>
            <td>$28</td>
            <td>4.4/5</td>
        </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: 7-in-1 USB-C Hub (Aluminum)</h2>
      <p>The 7-in-1 aluminum USB-C hub won because it covers every port a knowledge worker actually needs — 4K HDMI, three USB-A 3.0 ports, SD and microSD slots, and 100W power delivery — in a compact aluminum body designed to dissipate heat under load. The port selection is the sweet spot: enough to handle a desk setup, not so many that the hub becomes a bulky brick you avoid carrying.</p>
      <p>The aluminum unibody is not just for looks. Hubs with plastic casings can overheat during sustained 4K HDMI output and large file transfers, causing the USB-A ports to drop speeds by half. The aluminum casing on this hub acts as a heatsink, and according to manufacturer specifications, it is designed to maintain transfer speeds under sustained 4K HDMI output and large file transfers. This is the detail that separates a hub you forget about from one that frustrates you daily.</p>
      <p>Power delivery pass-through is the feature that makes this hub a permanent desk companion. You plug your MacBook charger into the hub, and the hub charges the MacBook while also connecting your monitor, drives, and peripherals through a single cable. Disconnect one cable from your laptop and you walk away with everything — monitor, charger, mouse, keyboard — left in place for next time.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
        <h2>7-in-1 USB-C Hub</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>4K HDMI output</strong> — mirror or extend to an external monitor at 30Hz</li>
          <li><strong>3 USB-A 3.0 ports</strong> — 5Gbps transfer speed for drives and peripherals</li>
          <li><strong>SD and microSD card slots</strong> — direct photo and video import for creators</li>
          <li><strong>100W Power Delivery pass-through</strong> — charge your laptop while using the hub</li>
          <li><strong>Aluminum unibody</strong> — matches MacBook aesthetic, dissipates heat under load</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=usb+c+hub+7+in+1&tag=toolwise20-20" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Check Current Price on Amazon</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Anker 555 USB-C Hub</h2>
      <p>The Anker 555 costs around $28 and offers the same 7-in-1 port selection as our top pick, with Anker's reputation for reliability backing it. It uses an aluminum body as well, and according to Anker's specifications it handles the same 4K monitor plus USB-A transfer workload without throttling. The build quality is excellent for the price.</p>
      <p>The trade-off is the cable. The Anker 555 has a shorter attached cable (about 6 inches) compared to our top pick's 8-inch cable, which can make placement awkward on taller laptop stands. It also runs slightly warmer under sustained load. If you can find it in stock and the cable length works for your setup, the Anker 555 is the best value in the category.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first spec to verify is power delivery wattage. If your MacBook charger is 96W or 100W, you need a hub that supports 100W PD pass-through — a hub rated for 60W will not pass enough power to charge a 16-inch MacBook under load. Hubs that list only "PD" without a wattage number are usually capped at 60W and should be avoided for larger laptops.</p>
      <p>Next, count the ports you actually use. Most workers need HDMI, two USB-A ports (mouse and keyboard), and power delivery — which a 7-in-1 hub covers. A 12-in-1 hub adds Ethernet, VGA, and extra USB-C ports that sound useful but add bulk and cost for ports most people never touch. Photographers should make sure both SD and microSD slots are present, since some hubs only include one.</p>
      <p>Common mistakes to avoid: do not buy a hub with a plastic body if you plan to drive a 4K monitor — it will overheat and throttle. Avoid hubs with detachable cables; the connection point is a failure risk and the cable gets lost in your bag. And skip "docking stations" that require external power at this price range — true docks cost $200+ and anything cheaper claiming to be a dock is just a hub with marketing.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Will a USB-C hub charge my MacBook while I use it?</summary>
          <p>Yes, if the hub supports Power Delivery pass-through. The 7-in-1 hub we recommend supports 100W PD pass-through, meaning you plug your MacBook charger into the hub and the hub charges the MacBook while also connecting your monitor, drives, and peripherals through one cable. Check the wattage rating — a 60W hub will not charge a 16-inch MacBook under full load.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Does a USB-C hub work with both Mac and Windows?</summary>
          <p>Yes. USB-C hubs are platform-agnostic. The same 7-in-1 hub works with MacBook Air, MacBook Pro, Dell XPS, Surface Laptop, and most modern Windows ultrabooks. The only compatibility check is whether your laptop's USB-C port supports DisplayPort Alt Mode for the HDMI output — nearly all laptops from 2020 onward do.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What is the difference between a USB-C hub and a Thunderbolt dock?</summary>
          <p>USB-C hubs use USB 3.0 speeds (5Gbps) and support one 4K display at 30Hz. Thunderbolt docks use 40Gbps Thunderbolt, support dual 4K displays at 60Hz, and cost $250 or more. For most workers who need one external monitor and a few USB peripherals, a $35 USB-C hub covers every port they actually need without the Thunderbolt premium.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

      <AffiliateDisclosure />
